# 13. 大人の味

Len: Humhumhuuum♪
Miku: Len, you sure have been in a good mood lately.
Len: Oh, can you tell? I'm still excited after meeting Kohane and An the other day. They were really nice.
Miku: That explains why you're so happy.
Miku: I am too. I think those two are going to become great friends.
Len: I think so too!
Len: Hehe. It's really making me look forward to meeting the other two. I can't wait.
Len: If I remember right, they're both guys, right? I can't wait for the chance to talk to them about music! It's going to be great!
MEIKO: Hehe. You sure are excited, aren't you?
MEIKO: I'm looking forward to meeting them as well. I wonder what they're like.
Len: Oh, but...
Miku: What's the matter?
Len: Well, I'm looking forward to meeting them and all, but part of me wonders if I ever will.
MEIKO: You don't think you'll get the chance? Why is that?
Len: Oh, it's just... Haha, never mind!
Len: O-Oh, MEIKO. Today's the day I finally want to try a black coffee!
MEIKO: Are you sure you don't want milk and sugar? You've always used it before.
Len: Yep, I don't need it. I'm an adult, after all.
Miku: Hehe. There's no need to force yourself.
Len: What's that supposed to mean?
Miku: I'm just saying there's no need to push yourself just because you don't want those two we haven't met yet to think you're too childish.
Len: Ngh! Th-That's not what I'm doing!
Miku: It's your choice, of course.
Miku: All you've had so far are café au lait with plenty of milk and sugar. Are you sure you're okay going straight to black?
Len: Of course! Up until now, I was just...uh... I was just drinking café au lait because that's what Rin was drinking.
Miku: Really?
MEIKO: Oh, is that so? I had no idea. Sorry for not noticing.
MEIKO: Well, here's your black coffee.
Len: Th-Thanks, MEIKO. Wow, this smells really...
Len: Bitter...
Miku: Huh? Len, did you say it smells bitter?
Len: Wha?! N-No! I said it smells delicious!
Len: W-Well, here we go!
Len: .....
Miku: Hehe. Len, you don't seem to be enjoying it much.
Len: That's...not true.
MEIKO: Len, you don't have to force yourself to drink it if you don't like it.
Miku: That's right. Besides, it's not as though being able to drink coffee black suddenly makes you an adult.
Len: But...
Miku: The amount of milk and sugar I add depends on how I'm feeling.
Miku: Some days I'm just in the mood for something different, so I'll have a nice café au lait myself.
Miku: Black coffee is reserved for the days I need a little extra kick in the morning.
Len: Oh, I didn't realize you switched things up like that.
Miku: Yep. After all, MEIKO takes so much care in brewing it. But I think it's just fine to go with whatever you're in the mood for on any given day.
MEIKO: Hehe. I agree with Miku. Besides, when you force yourself to do something, you won't be able to keep it up for very long.
Len: Right.
Len: Thanks, Miku, MEIKO.
Len: All right, I'll take that milk and sugar after all. I don't want to waste the coffee after you went to the trouble of brewing it, MEIKO.
Len: I guess I can wait a little longer before I get used to drinking my coffee black.
Len: It might not be so bad being the kind of grown up who likes drinking café au lait, either.
Miku: Yeah, I don't see anything wrong with that.
MEIKO: I agree. I think that way of thinking suits you, Len.
Len: Hehe. Thanks.
Len: Yeah, this is better. I guess I just prefer café au lait.
Len: Mm... It really does taste better with milk and sugar. I already finished it.
Len: All right, I'm going to go introduce myself to those two.
Miku: All right. Be careful.
MEIKO: Have fun.
Len: Will do! Oh, I almost forgot.
Len: MEIKO, that café au lait was great! Thanks again!
MEIKO: Hehe. You're welcome.
Len: All right, I'm off!
Miku: I think Len would be better off just being himself instead of always trying so hard to act like an adult.
MEIKO: Hehe. I'm sure he'll realize the same thing soon enough.
Miku: Yeah, you're probably right.
